\chapter{Resource intensity of the economy ($R$)}
\label{chap:resource_intensity}
%#############################################################
%\epigraph{The conservation of natural resources is the fundamental problem.
% Unless we solve that problem it will avail us little to solve all the others.}
%{Theodore Roosevelt}
\epigraph{Without natural resources, life itself is impossible. From birth to 
death, natural resources, transformed for human use, feed, clothe, shelter, and
transport us. \ldots
% Upon them we depend for every material necessity, comfort, convenience, and protection in our lives.
Without abundant resources, prosperity is out of reach.}
{Gifford Pinchot}

The previous chapter addressed the sustainability implications of 
economic affluence, the $A$ term in the IPARC equation (Equation~\ref{eq:IPARC}). 
Because the economy is society's metabolism, economic growth and increasing affluence
mean more natural resources must be consumed. 
This chapter explores the sustainability implications of resource acquisition and consumption.

Whether we are aware of it or not, 
all plant, animal, and human life on Earth depends on natural resources for survival.
Where would you be without air and water to breathe and drink?
Without minerals to make cars?
Without timber to build homes?
Without healthy soil to grow food?
Without oceans and atmosphere to accept wastes?
Without coal, oil, and methane to make electricity, gasoline, and natural gas?
Nowhere.

\subsection*{Definitions}
An intensity is like an efficiency, except the numerator and denominator have 
different units.
A furnace that burns a quantity of natural gas that releases 100 btus of heat might
only deliver 96 of those btus to your house.
Such a furnace has an \emph{efficiency} of 96\% (btus delivered per btus input).
A natural gas power plant might burn gas at a rate that releases 300 MW of heat to generate
100 MW of electricity. 
Such a power plant has an efficiency of 33.3\%.
In both cases, the input and output have the same units of energy, btus in one case
and MW in the other.
On the other hand, an \emph{intensity} has \emph{different} units.
A vehicle's miles per gallon is an intensity.
Carbon emissions per ton of freight per mile moved is an intensity.
It is \emph{intensive} because total carbon emissions depend on the number of tons
moved and the total km they travel.

Imagine a coal-fired power plant that generates electricity, which charges
an electric car. 
The coal is the \emph{primary} energy source. 
The electricity is \emph{secondary}.
Hydro, solar, and wind are all primary energy sources. 
So are coal, crude oil, and natural gas.
In contrast, gasoline is a refined fuel. As such, it is the \emph{product} of 
an industrial process that uses energy.
We can judge that process on its efficiency and energy return on investment (EROI) --
see Section \ref{sec:eroi}.

We define a \emph{resource} as a primary input to the economy. 
As such, a resource is something \emph{extracted} from the natural world.
It is something provisioned by the ecosystem (to use the language of Section 
\ref{sec:ecosystem_services}).
Timber is a resource. Iron ore is a resource. Water is a resource.
Each resource can be transformed multiple times \emph{within} the economy.
Timber might become 2$\times$4s, plywood, toothpicks, and mulch.
Iron ore might become steel, then sheet metal, and then a toaster.
Water might be ice, a sports drink, and Play-Doh.
*** clarify definition of agriculture.***
Resources must be extracted before they can be consumed and, following Equation
\ref{eq:PCbalance}, everything that is extracted is consumed.

The $R$ term in the IPARC equation is the resource intensity of the economy.
$R$ is defined as
%
\begin{equation}\label{eq:R}
  R = \frac{\textrm{resources extracted}}{\textrm{\$ GDP}} \; .
\end{equation}
%
$R$ measures how much of each resource is used by the economy to create
a single dollar of GDP.
Figure~\ref{fig:total_material_use} shows rates of consumption of natural resources
aggregated into important categories of biomass, ores and industrial minerals, and 
construction minerals.
In 2005, the world economy used about 19 Gt of biomass, 6.7 Gt of ores and 
industrial minerals, and about 22 Gt of construction materials
to produce about \$81.5 trillion dollars of GDP. 
One Gt is $10^9$~tons (or $10^{12}$~kg) and a trillion dollars is \${}$10^{12}$.
Thus, each dollar of GDP produced used about 0.25 kg of biomass, 
0.086 kg of ores and minerals, and 0.27 kg of construction materials. 
A full accounting of the resource intensity of the economy ($R$)
yields a long list of numbers, like a huge grocery list,
each giving the amount of a single resource needed to make \$1 of GDP. 
This chapter discusses sustainability implications for a few resources,
with energy providing the prime example at the end. 

Resource intensity can be measured and quantified at the whole-economy level,
as in the examples above.
But resource intensity can also be quantified per economic sector.
Clearly, the manufacturing sector of the economy requires resources to function.
Raw materials (such as copper and minerals) are required to make
finished goods (such as sewing machines and mobile phones).
But all sectors, even the service sector, need resources.
Consider the simple example of a haircut.
The stylist arrives at the salon in a vehicle
(which requires iron ore, copper, and other natural resources to manufacture; 
perhaps refined liquid fuel to operate; and 
an atmosphere that is a source of oxygen and which absorbs CO$_2$ and water, the products of combustion).
The stylist uses electric clippers and a hairdryer during each appointment
(which require both natural resources to manufacture and electricity to operate).
You sit in a fancy chair 
(which contains metals and plastics) and
drive to and from the appointment
(on roads made of tar or cement).
There is no escaping the dependence on resources to run an economy, 
even in the service sector. 


