\section{Strong and weak sustainability for resources}%% extraction and consumption}
\label{sec:strong_weak_sust}
%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%

A significant sustainability challenge 
is extracting and consuming natural resources\index{resources!natural}
at a sustainable rate.
When considering the sustainability of resource extraction and consumption, 
it is helpful to consider the strong and weak sustainability categories 
introduced in Section~\ref{sec:what_is_sustainability}.


%++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++
\subsection{Strong sustainability}\index{sustainability!strong}
\label{sec:resources_strong_sustainability}
%++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++

Resources can be classified as ``renewable''\index{resources!renewable} or
``nonrenewable,''\index{resources!nonrenewable}
based on their regeneration rates.\index{regeneration rate!of resources}
Resources, such as the Sun,
that are expected to exist for millennia 
are classified as renewable.
Resources that regenerate quickly (on the order of decades), 
such as forests and other biomass,
are also classified as renewable.
Resources that regenerate slowly or not at all, such as fossil fuels,
are classified as nonrenewable.

Whether or not a resource is renewable affects the sustainability of its 
extraction and consumption,
per definitions of strong and weak sustainability.
A criterion for ``strong sustainability'' is 
extracting and consuming resources 
at a rate less than their natural regeneration rates.
We can interpret two of Herman Daly's~\cite{Daly1996} criteria
(see Section~\ref{sec:Sdefns})
as a definition of strong sustainability:
%
\begin{enumerate}

  \item Renewable resources, such as fish, soil, and groundwater, 
        must be used no faster
        than the rate at which they regenerate.

  \item Nonrenewable resources, such as minerals and fossil fuels,
        must be used no faster
        than renewable substitutes for them can be put into place.
        
\end{enumerate}
%


The economy, being society's metabolism,\index{economy!as society's metabolism}
is one aspect of life that also depends on natural resources
for its survival.
Indeed, we can say that the economy \emph{runs} on natural resources.\index{resources!natural}
All goods and the infrastructure for all services depend
on manufactured objects of all types:
cars and the roads on which they travel, 
homes and the utilities that sustain life,
food and the refrigerators that maintain freshness,
toilets and the sewer systems that remove wastes.
Furthermore, the operation of all these systems requires energy.

Although any raw material can be essential for a given product,
the European Commission maintains a list Critical Raw Materials (CRMs)\index{materials!critical!raw}
with special importance across a wide range of industries.
See Table~\ref{tab:CRMs} for critical materials and industries.
One interesting feature of Table~\ref{tab:CRMs} is the large number of critical raw materials.
Another interesting feature of Table~\ref{tab:CRMs} is the breadth of application; 
most of the critical materials are used throughout the economy.

