\section{Energy intensity of the economy}
\label{sec:energy_intensity_of_the_economy}
%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%

Continuing the \href{https://en.wiktionary.org/wiki/explication}{explication}
of the IPARC identity, 
we form a term for the primary energy intensity ($I_{ep}$) of the world economy
as an example for resource intensity of the economy ($R$).
$I_{ep}$ is the amount of primary energy required to create one unit (dollar) of
world GDP. 
Of course, many other resources are \emph{also} required to create a unit of GDP
but we use energy as the prime example.
The energy intensity of the economy is formed
by dividing primary energy consumption ($E_p$) 
by world GDP,
that is, \ dividing Figure~\ref{fig:PrimaryEnergyGraph} 
by Figure~\ref{fig:GDPGraph-Nordhaus}.
The result is Figure~\ref{fig:EnergyIntensityGraph-Nordhaus}.

