# Create data for the energy intensity of the economy.
energy_intensity <- dplyr::inner_join(
  # Get the primary energy data
  primary_energy %>% 
    dplyr::group_by(Year) %>% 
    dplyr::summarise(energy_TWh = sum(energy_TWh)), 
  # Get the GDP data
  world_gdp_Nordhaus %>% 
    dplyr::select(Year, world_gdp_2017_intl_dollars), 
  by = "Year"
) %>% 
  dplyr::mutate(
    energy_per_GDP_MJ_per_dollar = energy_TWh * 3600000000 / world_gdp_2017_intl_dollars  # 3600000000 MJ / TWh
  ) 
energy_intensity %>% 
  ggplot2::ggplot(mapping = ggplot2::aes_string(x = "Year", y = "energy_per_GDP_MJ_per_dollar")) + 
  ggplot2::geom_line(size = 1, colour = mc_title_blue) + 
  ggplot2::scale_y_continuous(limits = c(0, NA)) +
  ggplot2::labs(x = NULL,
                y = expression(atop("Prim. energy intensity (R) [MJ/2017 Intl. $]"))) +
  MKHthemes::xy_theme()
@


Figure~\ref{fig:EnergyIntensityGraph-Nordhaus} shows that
the primary energy intensity of the world economy ($I_{ep}$) has fallen from 
15 to 4 MJ/2017 international dollar across the last two centuries. 
*** trillion? ***
The decline is caused by the fact that the world economy's GDP 
(Figure~\ref{fig:GDPGraph-Nordhaus}) 
has been growing at a faster rate (in \%/year terms) than primary energy consumption 
(Figure~\ref{fig:PrimaryEnergyGraph}).
**** Innovation, in the form of energy efficiency,
has lead to greater economic productivity, that is economic growth. ****

One reason that we are interested in the energy intensity of the economy is that 
energy use is a source of CO$_2$ emissions.
We can look at a restricted interpretation of Equation~\ref{eq:IPARC}, 
which considers only CO$_2$ emissions on the left-hand side of the equation
and the energy intensity of the economy ($I_{ep}$) instead of $R$ on the right-hand side.
When $I_{ep}$ falls, downward pressure is placed on CO$_2$ emissions.
Whether CO$_2$ emissions \emph{actually} decrease
depends on the rates of increase or decline of the other terms 
on the right side of Equation~\ref{eq:IPARC}.
Figure~\ref{fig:CarbonEmissionsGraph} shows that CO$_2$ emissions have been growing over time.
So, other terms on the right side of the IPARC identity 
are growing faster than energy intensity of the economy is declining
(see Section \ref{sec:revisit_IPARC}).

There are many suggested ways to reduce the resource intensity of the economy ($R$)
or the prime example the energy intensity of economic activity ($I_{ep}$).
First, increasing energy efficiency (through efficiency standards or mandates)
can decrease the energy consumption for end uses. 
Examples include corporate average fuel economy (CAFE) standards for vehicles 
in the U.S.\
%% a citation for CAFE  is complicated. We could cite the law (CFR) but that's 
%% not very helpful because the law just delegates rule-making responsibility to 
%% US DoT, who then delegates to NHTSA. NHTSA has a web page but experience is that
%% government web pages change at least every 4 years. 
%% The wikipedia article is good, but I feel like with CAFE define, people can 
%% A) understand from context and B) google if they want more.
and mandates for LED lighting in many countries.
Another way to reduce the energy intensity of an economy is to move 
away from a manufacturing economy toward a service economy.
However, as shown in the haircut example at the beginning of this chapter,
the need for resources never goes away, even in a service economy. 
In fact, shifting to a service economy often introduces problem-shifting, 
as finished goods are imported and manufacturing heads off shore~\cite{Hardt:2018aa}.


